SIMPLE: idiotism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Idiotism
<hw>Id"i*ot*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>idiotisme</ets>, L. <ets>idiotismus</ets> the way of fashion of a
private person, the common or vulgar manner of speaking, Gr. <?/, fr.
<?/ to put into or use common language, fr. <?/. See
<er>Idiot</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An idiom; a form, mode of
expression, or signification, peculiar to a language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Scholars sometimes give terminations and <qex>idiotisms</qex>,
suitable to their native language, unto words newly invented.</q>
<rj><qau>M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lack of knowledge or mental capacity; idiocy;
foolishness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Worse than mere ignorance or <qex>idiotism</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shaftesbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The running that adventure is the greatist
<qex>idiotism</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Idiotize</ent>⟦br⟧
